{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":1177,"record_hash":"sha256:205eb281b4eea554982c69425744ac4236649835d74c762ad68509d6a5d89997","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:22:46.048Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: abc676\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 4487\nOutput:\n## Runtime Boundary\n\nDo not make this a microservice system for v1. Use a modular monolith: one\nrepository, one deployable service, one mounted volume, clean internal modules.\n\nPreferred production boundary:\n\n```text\nAgent Trail app\n  HTTP routes / API / page rendering\n  GitHub public PR lookup\n  internal generation module\n  local repository cache\n  but-agentlog projection API\n```\n\nThe cleanest v1 implementation is a small Rust web app, likely Axum or similar,\nthat links the `but-agentlog` public/read projection API directly. That avoids\nNAPI, helper binaries, and service-to-service HTTP. It also keeps the filesystem\nwork in the same runtime that owns the volume.\n\nThe internal generation function should be boring:\n\n```text\ngenerate_agent_trail(request: AgentTrailProjectionRequest)\n  -> AgentTrailProjectionResult\n```\n\nThe request should include:\n\n- `repoPath` or a future explicit GitMeta source handle\n- `metadataOid`\n- `pr`: Agent Trail host, GitHub repo id, owner, repo, PR number, base ref,\n  head ref, and head SHA\n- `limits`: max sessions, turns, records, bytes per record, total bytes, and\n  runtime deadline\n- `projectionVersion`\n\nThe response should include only the public projection and status/warning\nfields. It must not include raw session keys, raw turn keys, provider session\nids, filesystem paths, `source_record`, or hidden/system/developer messages.\n\nIf the project later chooses a Node/Next monolith for web ergonomics, then use\nGitButler's NAPI pattern with a dedicated Agent Trail package. GitButler already\nhas a working NAPI shape:\n\n- `crates/but-api` marks Rust APIs with `#[but_api(napi)]`\n- `crates/but-napi` is a `cdylib` that links the generated exports\n- `packages/but-sdk` runs `@napi-rs/cli`, ships generated `index.js`,\n  `index.d.ts`, and platform `.node` artifacts\n\nIn that case, borrow the packaging pattern, not the broad desktop API surface.\nDo not make Agent Trail depend on the full `@g\n[TRUNCATED]\nGit cache.\n\nBetter deployment shape: a container/VM worker with a mounted volume.\n\n- Fly.io volumes are local persistent storage for Fly Machines\n  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n- Render paid web services, private services, and background workers can attach\n  persistent disks; default service filesystems are ephemeral\n  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n- Railway volumes mount read/write persistent storage into a service\n  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n\nImplication: deploy the Agent Trail app as a long-lived container with a\npersistent volume. Do not use Vercel/serverless for generation.\n\n### Rust / Node Boundary\n\nNAPI is the cleanest Rust-to-Node bridge only if the Agent Trail app is a Node\nweb process. A Rust web app can avoid the bridge entirely.\n\nRelevant findings:\n\n- Node-API is ABI-stable across Node versions, which makes it the right native\n  addon foundation\n  ([Node-API docs](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html)).\n- `napi-rs` can build Rust native addons and emit platform-suffixed `.node`\n  artifacts such as `index.darwin-x64.node`\n  ([napi-rs CLI](https://napi-rs.github.io/napi-rs/cli/)).\n- A helper binary is operationally simpler than NAPI in some deployments because\n  it isolates crashes and avoids native addon bundling, but it still requires\n  binary packaging, filesystem access, `git`, and a cache.\n- WASM/WASI is a bad fit. Node's WASI support is still marked experimental, and\n  Rust's base WASI target does not support process spawning. Agent Trail wants\n  real Git repository behavior, so WASM adds friction without removing the hard\n  dependency.\n\nImplication: prefer a Rust web app that links the projection API directly. If\nthe app must run on Node, prefer a dedicated `but-agenttrail-napi` package and\nexternalize it from Next bundling.\n\n### Current Recommendation\n\nBuild this as one deployable Agent Trail app:\n\n- HTTP/API/page layer: URL replacement, GitHub PR lookup, public JSON contract,\n  status polling, snapshot route, and UI.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:22:46.048Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}